Predicting Sales on Black Friday

Chip Irek

1 - Problem statement

Predict sales.

Build a model to predict the purchase amount of a customer using attributes which will help create personalized offer for customers against different products.

2 - Data dictionary

It looks like we have 12 different columns, each representing a corresponding variable below.

  • User_ID: Unique identifier of shopper.
  • Product_ID: Unique identifier of product. (No key given)
  • Gender: Sex of shopper.
  • Age: Age of shopper split into bins.
  • Occupation: Occupation of shopper. (No key given)
  • City_Category: Residence location of shopper. (No key given)
  • Stay_In_Current_City_Years: Number of years stay in current city.
  • Marital_Status: Marital status of shopper.
  • Product_Category_1: Product category of purchase.
  • Product_Category_2: Product may belong to other category.
  • Product_Category_3: Product may belong to other category.
  • Purchase: Purchase amount in dollars.

Hackathon winner was ~2500

6 - Observations about the data

Imputation

The only missing values are in vectors Product_Category_2 and Product_Category_3.

# convert the acceptable NAs to new dummy category
dataset.training[is.na(dataset.training)] <- 'None'

# coerse the datatypes to their intended meaning
dataset.training$User_ID <- as.integer(as.character(dataset.training$User_ID))
dataset.training$Product_ID <- as.integer(dataset.training$Product_ID)
dataset.training$Marital_Status <- as.factor(as.character(dataset.training$Marital_Status))
dataset.training$Product_Category_1 <- as.factor(as.character(dataset.training$Product_Category_1))
dataset.training$Product_Category_2 <- as.factor(as.character(dataset.training$Product_Category_2))
dataset.training$Product_Category_3 <- as.factor(as.character(dataset.training$Product_Category_3))

Outliers

Each predictor has purchases that are extreme outliers.

# if there are outliers, remove them
outliers <- boxplot(dataset.training$Purchase, plot=F)$out
if (length(outliers) > 0) {
  dataset.training <- dataset.training[-which(dataset.training$Purchase %in% outliers),]
  }

Correlation

No visually obvious correlation for any predictor.

Set up the test harness

# Define the training control
train.control <- trainControl(method = 'cv', number = 5)

Set up the tuning grid for XGBoost

I experimented in another notebook to get these parameters.

tune.grid.for.xgb <- expand.grid(nrounds=50,
                                lambda=10,
                                alpha=1,
                                eta=0.3
)

Train the models:

# train linear regression
model.lm <- train(Purchase ~ ., 
                 data=dataset.training,
                 method='lm', 
                 tuneLength=5, 
                 trControl=train.control)

# train xgboost
model.xgb <- train(Purchase ~., 
                   data=dataset.training.onehot_encoded,
                   method="xgbLinear",
                   trControl=train.control,
                   tuneGrid=tune.grid.for.xgb,
                   tuneLength=5
                   )

# train random forest
model.rf <- train(Purchase ~ ., 
                 data=dataset.training,
                 method='ranger', 
                 tuneLength=5, 
                 trControl=train.control)

Compare LM, XGB, and RF

# Compare model performances using resample()
models.compared <- resamples(list(`Linear Regression`=model.lm,
                                  `XGBoost`=model.xgb,
                                  `Random Forest`=model.rf
                                  ))
# Summary of the models performances
summary(models.compared)

7 - Model observations so far

Linear regression performs the worst. Random Forest (with no tuning or feature engineering at all) performs as well as XGBoost which took a lot of effort in tuning. In production I would go with Random Forest because it can rolled out quickly and automated easily.

Lets see if we can improve the results further.

8 - Feature engineering to improve RMSE score

Create new features Product_Count_For_Customer and Customer_Count_For_Product, and Mean_Product_Price
# Product_Count_For_Customer
Product_Count_For_Customer <- ddply(dataset.training.onehot_encoded, .(User_ID), nrow)
names(Product_Count_For_Customer)[2] <- "Product_Count_For_Customer"
dataset.training.onehot_encoded <- merge(dataset.training.onehot_encoded, Product_Count_For_Customer, by="User_ID")

# Customer_Count_For_Product
Customer_Count_For_Product <- ddply(dataset.training.onehot_encoded, .(Product_ID), nrow)
names(Customer_Count_For_Product)[2] <- "Customer_Count_For_Product"
dataset.training.onehot_encoded <- merge(dataset.training.onehot_encoded, Customer_Count_For_Product, by="Product_ID")

# Mean_Product_Price
Mean_Product_Price <- ddply(dataset.training.onehot_encoded, .(Product_ID), summarize, Mean_Product_Price=mean(Purchase))
dataset.training.onehot_encoded <- merge(dataset.training.onehot_encoded, Mean_Product_Price, by="Product_ID")

Train the models:

# train linear regression
model.lm <- train(Purchase ~ ., 
                 data=dataset.training,
                 method='lm', 
                 tuneLength=5, 
                 trControl=train.control)

# train xgboost
model.xgb <- train(Purchase ~., 
                   data=dataset.training.onehot_encoded,
                   method="xgbLinear",
                   trControl=train.control,
                   tuneGrid=tune.grid.for.xgb,
                   tuneLength=5
                   )

# train random forest
model.rf <- train(Purchase ~ ., 
                 data=dataset.training,
                 method='ranger', 
                 tuneLength=5, 
                 trControl=train.control)

Compare LM, XGB, and RF

                                  `XGBoost`=model.xgb,

Conclusion

Model performance was the same for all algorthims, until feature engineering was introduced. Adding features that emphasized small variances in the data allowed XGBoost to vastly outperform linear regression and random forest.
